abstract: A new exhibition at the New-York Historical Society sheds light on little-known amateur and professional black basketball teams from the first half of the 20th century.
snippet: A new exhibition at the New-York Historical Society sheds light on little-known amateur and professional black basketball teams from the first half of the 20th century.
lead_paragraph: ROSENA DISERY, a teenager at the New York African Free School in 1820, surely knew nothing about basketball when she stitched a silk-on-wool sampler with words from the poem “Self-Love and Truth Incompatible.”
headline_main: Remembering the ‘Black Fives’ of Pro Basketball
headline_print_headline: Remembering the ‘Black Fives’ of Pro Basketball

abstract: A crisis strikes the heart of basketball country: For the first time in nearly a decade, none of Indiana’s Division I men’s teams have made the N.C.A.A. tournament.
snippet: A crisis strikes the heart of basketball country: For the first time in nearly a decade, none of Indiana’s Division I men’s teams have made the N.C.A.A. tournament.
lead_paragraph: With every missed shot, there was a collective groan. With every turnover, a loud sigh. It was as if the college basketball fans inside 33 Brick Street, a sports bar in Larry Bird’s hometown, French Lick, were speaking for the entire basketball-crazed state of Indiana.

abstract: The photographer and author of “Open City” and “Every Day Is for the Thief” says the novel is overrated. “The writers I find most interesting find ways to escape it.”

abstract: Artists who have moved to the Big Easy reflect on the influences and inspiration they find in their adopted home.
snippet: Artists who have moved to the Big Easy reflect on the influences and inspiration they find in their adopted home.
lead_paragraph: On a recent Monday night the usual suspects gathered at BJ’s, a dive in the Ninth Ward of New Orleans. They were there, as many are every Monday, to see one of the city’s premier bands, King James & the Special Men. Grizzled rockers in leather jackets leaned against the worn walls, smoking. Regulars hunched over the sticky bar drinking cheap draft beer. A group of clean-cut guys on a bachelor party binge swayed unsteadily near a vat of free red beans and rice and eyed a klatch of college girls in fluorescent hair and fishnets.
